value.0: Ah, I think this may be just the thing. <StartAction>[He sizes you up.]</Start>
Fine. I'm not going to wait here forever if you needed someone to join up with.
I know you aren't from around here. And I know you've killed many Luskans. Sounds like we're in the same business. I say we join up and we can kill the whole lot of them.
You're talking to someone who has killed more Luskans in a single day than you've met your entire entire life. All I needed was to see the same look in your eyes. So are we joining up or not?
Bah. I'm not one for big groups. Too little loot to share and less killing for me.
Come back if you're by your lonesome. I'm not going to wait here forever if you needed someone to back you up.
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> Nah. I'd rather go at it alone. We'll talk if it's just you by yourself.
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> Yeah? Maybe you're right. Don't dissappoint me.
You point and I'll shoot. I'll be taking some of the spoils, of course.
Hmm... what?
Then let's keep moving.
<StartAction>[He scoffs.]</Start> Do you seriously think you don't need my help?
A wise choice. We have more Luskans to kill.
It's your funeral. I just won't be there to watch it.
Don't we all. You can ask, but don't expect any answers.
Well, it's because tracking and hunting help put things in perspective. Out in the wild... well, the whole predator-prey relationship is a little more honest.
If you like the wilds, why are you in Luskan?
I've been on both sides, prey and predator - and if you think you're a predator, you're usually wrong, you're always someone's prey.
Don't know. Maybe someone, maybe no one - but chances are, I'll find out someday unless I find them first.
Luskans? Don't give it much thought. Most of them aren't human beings, anyway, they usually give up any shred of morality or dignity as part of the toll at the front gate.
Because they deserve it? At least in my stint in Neverwinter, the soldiers and thieves operate with some shred of purpose or morality. Luskan? It's not even worth hating them.
I used to be a soldier for them, and I can rightly say I didn't care much for the work - their reward system is a double-edged blade.
They tried to draft me into rougher and rougher jobs - and then they wanted to make some changes in my life. So I left, and that's it.
Yeah... you don't need to know every twist and turn in the story, believe me. Otherwise, you might not be able to sleep at night, and we wouldn't want that.
There's more... there was always more, and that was the problem.
Sometimes you realize that the more you do, the less free you get. And I'm someone who likes their space, some room to move.
Ever had to do something you don't like - but there's no reason you have to do it except someone ordered you to do it? That doesn't sit well with me.

I don't follow orders, and I don't listen to any man or woman, telling me what to do. I go where I want, kill who I want, do what I want. And by the hells anyone who gets in my way better know how to run.
Anyways, enough talk. I didn't join for some idle chit chatter. Let's get back to it.
What do you want?
Perhaps you'll think differently with a foot of steel in your gut.
I don't feel like talking right now. Goodbye.
How could you possibly know that?
We can join up. Welcome the to the team.
Fine. Forget I asked.
<StartCheck>[Persuade]</Start> Believe me, where we're going there's going to be a whole lot of Luskanites to kill.
Never mind.
I think we need to part ways.
No, never mind.
Yes, I've made up my mind.
I had some questions for you.
Why did you become a ranger?
So which are you - predator or prey?
Because Luskans *are* my prey. I think I've told you enough of my life story for now.
You seem to have some problems with Luskans.
Why do you hate them so much?
I've heard enough.
Are you sure?
What are you talking about?
I'd like to buy off some of the loot that you picked up.
I'd like to buy off some of the loot that you picked up.
